                <section id="what-is-gan" class="mb-16">
                    <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6 border border-slate-200 shadow-sm">
                    <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-brandBlue uppercase italic mb-6">1. GaN Semiconductor Technology: What to Verify in Chip Specs</h2>
                    <p class="text-slate-600 mb-4">For OEM buyers sourcing chargers, understanding GaN at the semiconductor level is not academic, it directly determines which chip supplier (Infineon CoolGaN, Navitas GaNFast, or Innoscience) your factory specs, and whether your product achieves the efficiency numbers you quote to retail buyers. Gallium Nitride (GaN) is a <strong>wide-bandgap semiconductor</strong>, a crystalline material that conducts electricity under specific conditions while blocking it under others. It's the same class of material that makes LED lights possible. In chargers, GaN replaces the silicon transistors that have been the industry standard for over 60 years.</p>
                    <p class="text-slate-600 mb-4">The key difference comes down to physics. GaN has a <strong>bandgap of 3.4 electronvolts (eV)</strong>, compared to silicon's 1.1 eV. This wider bandgap means GaN can handle higher voltages before breaking down, switch on and off at much higher frequencies, and do both with significantly less energy wasted as heat.</p>
                    <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-6 mb-6">
                        <h3 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-4">The Bandgap Advantage :  Why It Matters</h3>
                        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-4 text-center">
                            <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-5">
                                <div class="text-3xl font-black text-brandBlue mb-2">3.4 eV</div>
                                <div class="text-xs text-slate-500 uppercase tracking-wider">GaN Bandgap</div>
                                <p class="text-slate-600 text-xs mt-2">Handles higher voltages without breakdown. Enables compact designs.</p>
                            </div>
                            <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-5">
                                <div class="text-3xl font-black text-slate-400 mb-2">1.1 eV</div>
                                <div class="text-xs text-slate-500 uppercase tracking-wider">Silicon Bandgap</div>
                                <p class="text-slate-600 text-xs mt-2">Lower threshold means more energy lost as heat during conversion.</p>
                            </div>
                            <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-5">
                                <div class="text-3xl font-black text-brandOrange mb-2">3×</div>
                                <div class="text-xs text-slate-500 uppercase tracking-wider">GaN Advantage</div>
                                <p class="text-slate-600 text-xs mt-2">Three times wider bandgap = fundamentally better power handling.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <p class="text-slate-600 mb-4">Think of it this way: silicon is like a narrow country road, it works, but traffic slows down when too many cars try to pass. GaN is like a multi-lane highway, electrons move faster, with less congestion (resistance), and less energy wasted as heat. This is why GaN chargers can be simultaneously <strong>smaller, cooler, and more powerful</strong> than their silicon counterparts.</p>
                    <p class="text-slate-600">According to <a href="https://epc-co.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-brandBlue hover:underline">Efficient Power Conversion (EPC)</a>, a leading GaN semiconductor manufacturer, GaN transistors can switch at frequencies 100× faster than silicon MOSFETs while achieving power conversion efficiency exceeding 99% in optimized designs.</p>

                    <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-6 mt-6 border border-brandOrange/30">
                      <h4 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-3">WOWOHCOOL Factory Data: GaN Chip Efficiency Comparison (65W Reference Design, 230V/50Hz)</h4>
                      <div class="overflow-x-auto">
                        <table class="w-full text-sm border border-slate-200 rounded-xl">
                          <thead class="bg-brandBlue text-white">
                            <tr>
                              <th class="text-left p-3 font-black uppercase text-xs">GaN Chip</th>
