                              <th class="text-center p-3 font-black uppercase text-xs">FOB Cost Impact</th>
                            </tr>
                          </thead>
                          <tbody>
                            <tr class="border-t border-slate-200"><td class="p-3 font-bold">CoolGaN G5 (IGT60R070D1)</td><td class="p-3 text-center">Infineon (Munich)</td><td class="p-3 text-center text-green-600 font-bold">94.7%</td><td class="p-3 text-center">58.3°C</td><td class="p-3 text-center">+$1.50-2.00</td></tr>
                            <tr class="border-t border-slate-200"><td class="p-3 font-bold">NV6169 GaNFast</td><td class="p-3 text-center">Navitas (US)</td><td class="p-3 text-center text-green-600 font-bold">93.2%</td><td class="p-3 text-center">61.7°C</td><td class="p-3 text-center">+$1.00-1.50</td></tr>
                            <tr><td class="p-3 font-bold">INN700D240A (8" GaN-on-Si)</td><td class="p-3 text-center">Innoscience (China)</td><td class="p-3 text-center text-green-600 font-bold">91.8%</td><td class="p-3 text-center">64.5°C</td><td class="p-3 text-center">Baseline</td></tr>
                          </tbody>
                        </table>
                      </div>
                      <p class="text-slate-500 text-xs mt-3">All measurements taken on WOWOHCOOL production line using Chroma 63600-series DC electronic load, 230V/50Hz input, 4-hour continuous 100% load burn-in. Ambient temperature: 25°C ±2°C. Efficiency measured at PCB output before USB-C connector. Individual unit results vary within ±0.5%.</p>
                    </div>
                    </div>
                </section>

                <section id="how-it-works" class="mb-16">
                    <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6 border border-slate-200 shadow-sm">
                    <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-brandBlue uppercase italic mb-6">2. Inside a GaN Charger: Component Architecture & Switching Frequency Fundamentals</h2>
                    <p class="text-slate-600 mb-4">When evaluating factory BOMs and negotiating component sourcing, OEM buyers need to understand what's inside the charger and why GaN's higher switching frequency changes every downstream design decision. A charger's job is to convert the alternating current (AC) from your wall outlet into the direct current (DC) your device needs. This conversion happens inside a component called a <strong>switched-mode power supply</strong>, where transistors rapidly switch on and off to regulate voltage and current.</p>
                    <p class="text-slate-600 mb-4">Traditional silicon transistors switch at frequencies of <strong>100-500 kHz</strong>. GaN transistors switch at <strong>1-10 MHz</strong>, up to 100× faster. This higher switching frequency is the root cause of every GaN advantage:</p>
                    <div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
                        <div class="flex gap-4">
                            <div class="w-10 h-10 bg-brandBlue rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-white font-black shrink-0">1</div>
                            <div>
                                <h3 class="font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Faster Switching = Smaller Components</h3>
                                <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">Higher frequency means the charger's transformer and capacitors can be physically smaller while handling the same power. This is why a 65W GaN charger is roughly the size of a credit card stack, while a 65W silicon charger is a palm-sized brick.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="flex gap-4">
                            <div class="w-10 h-10 bg-brandBlue rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-white font-black shrink-0">2</div>
                            <div>
                                <h3 class="font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Less Energy Lost as Heat</h3>
                                <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">In a silicon charger, roughly 15-20% of input power becomes waste heat. In a GaN charger, only 3-5% is lost. Less waste heat means no need for bulky heat sinks and safer long-term operation.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="flex gap-4">
                            <div class="w-10 h-10 bg-brandBlue rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-white font-black shrink-0">3</div>
                            <div>
                                <h3 class="font-bold text-slate-900 mb-1">Higher Power Density</h3>
                                <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">Power density measures how much wattage fits in a given volume. GaN achieves 1.5-2W per cubic centimeter vs silicon's 0.5-0.8W/cc, packing 2-3× more power into the same space.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

