                <section id="misconceptions" class="mb-16">
                    <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6 border border-slate-200 shadow-sm">
                    <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-brandBlue uppercase italic mb-6">6. GaN Sourcing Myths: What Procurement Teams Get Wrong About Cost, Speed & Quality</h2>
                    <p class="text-slate-600 mb-4">These four misconceptions trip up even experienced B2B buyers, each one has direct consequences for your product specification, factory selection, and unit economics.</p>
                    <div class="space-y-6">
                        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-6">
                            <h3 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-2">Myth: "GaN chargers charge faster than regular chargers"</h3>
                            <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm"><strong>Reality:</strong> A 65W charger delivers 65W regardless of whether it uses GaN or silicon. The wattage determines speed, not the material. GaN's real speed advantage is <strong>sustained performance</strong>: silicon chargers often thermally throttle after 15-20 minutes, dropping from 65W to 30-45W. GaN chargers maintain full output continuously, so your device reaches full charge faster in practice.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-6">
                            <h3 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-2">Myth: "All small chargers are GaN"</h3>
                            <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm"><strong>Reality:</strong> Some manufacturers market compact silicon chargers as "GaN-like" or use misleading branding. Check the specifications, genuine GaN chargers will explicitly state "GaN" or "Gallium Nitride" in the technical details. If a charger at 65W+ is genuinely tiny and doesn't get hot, it's likely GaN. If it's small but runs hot, it's probably silicon pushed to its thermal limits.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-6">
                            <h3 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-2">Myth: "More ports = better charger"</h3>
                            <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm"><strong>Reality:</strong> A 100W GaN charger with 4 ports shares that 100W among all connected devices. Plug in a laptop (65W) + phone (20W) + earbuds (5W) = 90W total, you're near the limit. Adding a fourth device means everything charges slower. The port count matters less than the <strong>total wattage budget</strong> and how intelligently the charger distributes power. Read our <a href="/blog/usb-c-pd-fast-charging-guide" class="text-brandBlue hover:underline">USB-C PD Fast Charging Guide</a> for more on power allocation.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-6">
                            <h3 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-2">Myth: "GaN chargers are expensive"</h3>
                            <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm"><strong>Reality:</strong> The price gap has narrowed dramatically. In 2026, a quality 65W GaN charger retails for $25-40, while an equivalent silicon charger costs $15-25. The $10-15 premium buys you half the size, better heat management, and roughly double the lifespan, excellent value for a product you use daily for years. GaN power IC costs are dropping 8-12% annually, further narrowing the gap.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    </div>
                </section>

