                <section id="how-to-choose" class="mb-16">
                    <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6 border border-slate-200 shadow-sm">
                    <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-brandBlue uppercase italic mb-6">8. GaN Charger Specification Checklist: Wattage, Ports, Certifications & Cable Matching</h2>
                    <div class="space-y-4">
                        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-6">
                            <h3 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-2">1. Match the Wattage to Your Devices</h3>
                            <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">Check your device's maximum charging speed. An iPhone charges at 20-27W, a MacBook Air at 30-45W, and a MacBook Pro at 65-140W. Buying a 100W charger for a phone is wasteful. Buying a 30W charger for a laptop means slow charging. <strong>Add up the wattage of devices you charge simultaneously</strong> to determine the total you need.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-6">
                            <h3 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-2">2. Count Your Ports</h3>
                            <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">Single-port chargers are simpler and cheaper. Dual-port chargers handle a laptop + phone. 3-4 port chargers cover a full desk setup. Remember: total wattage is shared across all ports. A "100W 4-port" charger doesn't deliver 100W to each port, it's 100W total, distributed dynamically.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-6">
                            <h3 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-2">3. Verify the GaN Generation</h3>
                            <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">GaN technology has evolved through generations. <strong>GaN V (5th generation, 2024-2026)</strong> offers the best performance with switching frequencies above 5MHz, reduced component count, and improved thermal efficiency. <a href="/blog/gan-generations-guide/" class="text-brandBlue hover:underline">Read our GaN Generations Guide</a> for a detailed comparison of GaN I vs III vs V.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-6">
                            <h3 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-2">4. Check Safety Certifications</h3>
                            <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">Look for CE (Europe), FCC (USA), and UL/ETL certification marks. These indicate the charger has passed independent safety testing. Avoid chargers with no visible certification marks, they may lack basic protection circuits. A quality GaN charger includes over-current, over-voltage, over-temperature, and short-circuit protection.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-6">
                            <h3 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-2">5. Don't Forget the Cable</h3>
                            <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">A 100W GaN charger with a cheap 3A cable delivers only 60W. For chargers above 60W, ensure you use a <strong>5A e-marked USB-C cable</strong>. For 140W+ PD 3.1 chargers, you need an <strong>EPR-rated cable</strong>. The cable is just as important as the charger, a bottleneck here negates your investment. Read our <a href="/blog/usb-c-pd-fast-charging-guide" class="text-brandBlue hover:underline">USB-C PD guide</a> for cable recommendations.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    </div>
                </section>

